File: /home/test/code/fingermoba/web/game.js — three edits, no other changes needed. No HTML change; the Godot-era `emulate_touch_from_mouse` note is irrelevant to this Phaser build (mouse already fires pointer events).

1) Paste the VirtualJoystick class above into game.js (top of file, before `class Game`).

2) In create(), after the WASD line `this.keys = this.input.keyboard.addKeys('W,A,S,D,UP,DOWN,LEFT,RIGHT');` add:
     this.stick = new VirtualJoystick(this, { radius: 70, deadZone: 0.12, depth: 12 });
   (depth 12 keeps it above the world/HUD bars but below the level-up modal at depth 20+; the class's canStart() already refuses to engage while this.paused/this.over, so it won't fight the upgrade cards or restart button.)

3) Replace the pointer block in moverPlayer(dt). Remove these old lines:
     const ptr = this.input.activePointer;
     if (!vx && !vy && ptr.isDown) {
       const a = Phaser.Math.Angle.Between(p.x, p.y, ptr.worldX, ptr.worldY);
       if (Phaser.Math.Distance.Between(p.x, p.y, ptr.worldX, ptr.worldY) > 6) { vx = Math.cos(a); vy = Math.sin(a); }
     }
   And insert in their place:
     if (!vx && !vy) {                 // WASD takes priority; else use the stick
       const jv = this.stick.vector;
       vx = jv.x; vy = jv.y;           // already analog 0..1 per axis
     }
   Keep the existing final block AS-IS but make it magnitude-aware so the joystick gives analog speed (WASD stays full speed because its hypot normalizes to 1). Change:
     if (vx || vy) { const l = Math.hypot(vx, vy); p.x += (vx/l)*this.stats.moveSpeed*dt; p.y += (vy/l)*this.stats.moveSpeed*dt; }
   to:
     if (vx || vy) {
       let l = Math.hypot(vx, vy);
       const speed = Math.min(l, 1) * this.stats.moveSpeed; // analog from stick, full from WASD
       p.x += (vx/l)*speed*dt; p.y += (vy/l)*speed*dt;
     }
   The rest of moverPlayer (clamp + obj sync) is unchanged.

Optional: update the on-screen hint text in makeHUD() from '按住朝手指方向移动' to '拖动摇杆移动' so the UI matches. Phaser API used (all stable in 3.80): this.input.on('pointerdown'|'pointermove'|'pointerup'|'pointerupoutside'|'gameout'), this.input.addPointer(n) for multitouch, pointer.id, pointer.worldX/worldY, this.add.circle().setStrokeStyle()/.setDepth()/.setVisible()/.setScrollFactor(0). No camera scroll/zoom in this scene, so worldX/worldY equal screen coords. Context7 was unreachable (network fetch failed) so this was verified against the known-stable 3.80 input API the existing code already relies on (activePointer.worldX/worldY).

crisp.gameConfig:
ROOT CAUSE (verified against phaser@3.80.1 dist source):
With scale.mode=FIT and width/height=540x960, Phaser creates a WebGL drawing buffer of exactly 540x960 *CSS px*. FIT then CSS-stretches the canvas to fill the screen. On a DPR=3 phone that 540-wide buffer is blown up to ~1620 physical px by the GPU/browser → upscaling a low-res buffer = blur + visible mosaic ("能看到马赛克"). Phaser 3's `resolution` config key still exists in 3.80.1 but is NON-FUNCTIONAL/deprecated (it does NOT enlarge the drawing buffer), so it is useless here. The drawing buffer must be enlarged manually by DPR and the world scaled back down with `zoom`.

THE FIX — keep your 540x960 logical world coordinates unchanged, but multiply the actual render resolution by devicePixelRatio and compensate with zoom:

```js
const LOGICAL_W = 540, LOGICAL_H = 960;
// cap DPR so very-high-DPR devices (3x) don't tank fill-rate; 2 is plenty crisp
const DPR = Math.min(window.devicePixelRatio || 1, 2);

new Phaser.Game({
  type: Phaser.AUTO,
  parent: 'game',
  backgroundColor: '#0b1020',
  scale: {
    mode: Phaser.Scale.FIT,
    autoCenter: Phaser.Scale.CENTER_BOTH,
    // Render the buffer at DPR x logical size -> matches physical device pixels
    width:  LOGICAL_W * DPR,
    height: LOGICAL_H * DPR,
    // Scale the whole world back down so 1 game unit == 1 logical unit.
    // All your existing W=540/H=960 coordinates keep working unchanged.
    zoom: 1 / DPR,
    autoRound: true        // round canvas display/style sizes -> no half-pixel CSS smear
  },
  render: {
    antialias: true,       // smooth WebGL sampling for your circles/rects/SVGs
    antialiasGL: true,     // request an MSAA-capable WebGL context
    roundPixels: false,    // keep AA on sub-pixel motion; do NOT enable for non-pixel-art
    pixelArt: false,       // MUST stay false (true would force antialias:false + roundPixels:true = blocky)
    mipmapFilter: 'LINEAR_MIPMAP_LINEAR', // crisp minification when SVG textures drawn smaller than rasterized
    powerPreference: 'high-performance'
  },
  scene: [Game]
});
```

Why this works: the WebGL drawing buffer is now LOGICAL*DPR (e.g. 1080x1920 on a 2x phone). FIT still letterboxes/centers it, but now the buffer already has ~1 backing pixel per physical screen pixel, so the browser is no longer upscaling a small buffer — pixels map 1:1 (or 1:DPR), eliminating the mosaic. `zoom:1/DPR` shrinks the rendered output back to logical size on screen, AND lets you keep every existing `W/2`, `H/2`, `H-90` coordinate exactly as written (the camera/world stays 540x960). `autoRound:true` stops fractional CSS canvas sizes that re-introduce browser smoothing. Keep your CSS as-is (#game{width:100vw;height:100vh}) and the viewport meta with initial-scale=1.

IMPORTANT for text/SVG textures specifically: with the bigger buffer, also bump rasterization resolution of any Phaser Text objects via `resolution: DPR` in the text style (e.g. this.add.text(x,y,str,{fontSize:'24px', resolution: DPR})) so HUD/labels are crisp too — the global config `resolution` is dead but the per-Text-style `resolution` IS functional in 3.80.1 (confirmed in source: GameObjects.Text reads style.resolution).

crisp.svgLoad:
Phaser 3.80.1 rasterizes an SVG to a texture at the pixel size you pass in the 3rd arg of load.svg. Verified in dist source: SVGFile reads config.width/height/scale and literally rewrites the SVG's width/height attributes (or viewBox * scale) before serializing to a Blob and decoding — so the resulting GPU texture's pixel dimensions == the width/height you give. Rasterize at HIGH resolution (display size * DPR, or just oversized), then scale the Game Object down with setDisplaySize — downscaling a hi-res texture stays crisp, upscaling a small one blurs.

```js
preload() {
  // Your SVG as a data: URI string (works in 3.80.1 load.svg).
  // For a pure inline SVG string you can also wrap it as a data URI:
  const svgString =
    '<svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 100 100">' +
    '<circle cx="50" cy="50" r="48" fill="#3aa0ff" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="4"/></svg>';
  const dataUri = 'data:image/svg+xml;charset=utf-8,' + encodeURIComponent(svgString);

  const DPR = Math.min(window.devicePixelRatio || 1, 2);
  // I want this icon to DISPLAY at ~64x64 logical px. Rasterize bigger so it never upscales.
  const DISPLAY = 64;
  const RASTER  = Math.ceil(DISPLAY * DPR * 2); // 2x headroom over device pixels -> always sharp

  // (A) load.svg with explicit width/height -> texture is RASTER x RASTER pixels:
  this.load.svg('hero', dataUri, { width: RASTER, height: RASTER });

  // (B) or scale relative to the SVG's intrinsic/viewBox size:
  // this.load.svg('hero', dataUri, { scale: RASTER / 100 }); // viewBox is 100 wide
}

create() {
  // Draw the hi-res texture, then shrink to the logical display size you actually want:
  const icon = this.add.image(W/2, H/2, 'hero');
  icon.setDisplaySize(64, 64);   // 64-logical-px on screen, sourced from a 256px texture => crisp
}
```

Alternative without the Loader (synchronous, also data-URI based): `this.textures.addBase64('hero', dataUri)` — BUT addBase64 rasterizes at the SVG's own intrinsic width/height only and gives NO width/height control, so to get high resolution you must bake a large width/height into the SVG markup itself (e.g. width="256" height="256"). load.svg with {width,height} is the better, controllable path.

Rule for choosing width/height: rasterWidth >= displayWidth * cappedDevicePixelRatio (a 2x multiplier on top gives safe headroom). Never rasterize at the small display size and then let Phaser/CSS upscale — that is exactly what produces the mosaic. Downscaling (raster bigger than display) + render.antialias:true + the LINEAR_MIPMAP_LINEAR mipmapFilter from the config keeps small-drawn SVGs sharp.
